Dr. Nadine Hachach-Haram is a surgeon, lecturer and clinical entrepreneur. She drew on her passion for innovation, education and global surgery to co-found Proximie, an augmented reality platform that allows doctors to virtually transport themselves into any operating room, anywhere in the world, to visually and practically interact in an operation from start to finish. From marking up a patient to providing real-time virtual presence in assisting and instructing on an operation, Proximie aims to provide safe, accessible and cost-effective surgery to every patient around the world. Dubbed the "future of surgery" by CNN, Proximie has gone from strength to strength and won multiple awards as well as being the main focus of the Foreign Press Association Science Story of the Year. It aims to revolutionize the delivery and education of healthcare by reducing the cost of that delivery while providing improved quality to the end patient, ensuring that every patient gets the best care, the first time, every time.

The information age connectivity through digital technology is a modern miracle. We can say it has broken down barriers of time and space, which separate people, and it's created a condition for an age where information ideas could be shared freely. But are these great accomplishments in digital technology really the endgame in terms of what can be achieved? I don't think so. And today I'd like to share with you how I believe digital technology can take us to even greater heights. I'm a surgeon by profession, and as I stand here today talking to all of you, 5,000,000,000 people around the world lack access to safe surgical care. 5,000,000,000 people. That's 70% of the world's population, who, according to the W H Shows Lancet Commission, can't even access simple surgical procedures as and when they need them. Let's zoom in on Sierra Leone, a country of 6,000,000 people where a recent study showed that there are only 10 qualified surgeons. That's one surgeon for every 600,000 people. The numbers are staggering and We don't even need to look that far If we look around us here in the U. S. A recent study reported that we need an extra 100,000 surgeons by 2030 to just keep up with the demand for routine surgical procedures. At the rate that we're going, we won't be meeting those numbers as a surgeon. This is a global issue that bothers me. It bothers me a lot because I've seen firsthand how lack of access to safe and affordable health care comm blight the lives of ordinary people. If you're a patient that needs an operation and there isn't a surgeon available, you left us some really difficult choices to wait to travel or not to have an operation at all. So what's the answer? Well, part of your carrying some of that solution with you today a smartphone, a tablet computer because for me, digital communications technology has the power to do so much more than just to allow us to shop online, to connect through social media platforms and to stay up to date. It has the power to help us solve some of the key issues that we face, like lack of access to vital surgical service is. And today I'd like to share with you an example of how I think we could make that possible. The history of surgeries filled with breakthroughs and how science and technology was able to help the surgeons of the day face. Their greatest challenge is if we go back. Several 100 years on Understanding of microbiology led to the development of antiseptic techniques, which played a big role in making sure patients were able to stay alive. Post surgery. Fast forward a few 100 years, and we developed Key Holder Arthroscopic surgery, which combines video technology and precision instruments to make surgery less invasive. And more recently, ah lot of you will be aware of robotic surgery. And what robotic springs to surgery is much like modern automated machinery, ultra precision. The ability to carry out procedures at the tiniest scales with a degree of accuracy that even surpasses the human hand. But robotic surgery also introduce something else to surgery. The idea that a surgeon doesn't actually have to be standing at the patient's bedside to deliver care that he could be looking at a screen and instructing a robot through a computer we call this remote surgery. It is incumbent on us to find solutions that sold these answers in a cost effective and scalable way so that everyone, no matter where they are in the world, can have these problems addressed. So what if I told you that you didn't really need $1,000,000 robot to provide remote surgery that all you need? It was a phone, a tablet or a computer, an Internet connection, a competent colleague on the ground and one magic ingredient augmented reality collaboration software. Using this augmented reality collaboration software, an expert surgeon can now virtually transport himself into any clinical setting simply by using this phone or tablet or computer. And he convince, Julian practically contracted an operation from start to finish, guiding and mentoring a local doctor through the procedure step by step. Well, enough of me telling you about it.
